<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-064-470  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 064 470.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  Jan 11 1990 v35 n1A p43(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Temporary engineers fill gaps at DoD contractors; confidence,hands-on experience, and a willingness to take risks arerequisite. (Department of Defense) (includes a related article onthe rights of contractors as employees)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Colborn, Kate.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Out-of-work engineers with defense-specific skills can find workon a contract or temporary basis through one of the many temporaryplacement agencies and defense contractors anticipating increaseduse of temporaries to supplement the reduced permanent workforce.andO;Many defense contractors point out, however, that contractors areusually the first to be let go when cut-backs start.andP;  Contractorswho previously could usually count on one contract after anotherat a company will now likely find that they will be released assoon as the contract is up.andP;  Government budget limitations and theeasing of tensions between the US and the Soviet Union areexpected to result in Department of Defense budget cuts through1998, according to the Electronic Industries Association.andP;  Ascompanies down-size, they find they must cope with holes in theirworkforce, which are often filled by temporaries.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Temporary Help ServicesOutlookMilitaryEmploymentTrendsContractorsUnited States. Department of DefenseEngineers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>